					<div class="bio">
						<h4>Sarah Aziza</h4>
												<p>Sarah Aziza is a Palestinian American writer, translator, and artist with roots in 'Ibdis and Deir al-Balah, Gaza. The recipient of a Fulbright fellowship and numerous grants from the Pulitzer Center for Crisis Reporting, she has lived and worked in Saudi Arabia, Algeria, Jordan, South Africa, the West Bank, and the United States. Her award-winning journalism, poetry, essays, and experimental nonfiction have appeared in <em>The New Yorker</em>, <em>The Baffler</em>, <em>Harper’s</em>, <em>Mizna</em>, <em>Lux</em>, <em>The Washington Post</em>, <em>The Intercept</em>, <em>The Rumpus</em>, <em>NPR</em>, <em>The Margins</em>, and <em>The Nation</em>, among other publications. She is also the author of <em>The Hollow Half</em>.</p>
					</div>
